Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
US President Barack Obama will arrive in Oslo, Norway to spend 26 hours and receive the Nobel Peace Prize, as the fourth US president in history.
The diploma, medal and cheque for $1.4 million will be awarded, among other things, for their exceptional efforts in strengthening world diplomacy and cooperation among nations.
The head of the White House and his wife Michelle will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning and they will have a lot to do.
First, a visit to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the committee that, in October, selected him from 172 individuals and 33 organisations.
Afterwards, the presidential couple is scheduled to meet with the King of Norway, Harald V, and Queen Sonia.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony in which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will be the fourth American president to receive it, though the third to receive it in office.
The White House has already announced that when he receives the award, he will speak about the Afghan war.
The President does not want to avoid the subject, knowing that he is receiving the award as president of a country that is currently at war in two countries.
His war efforts were further increased by sending additional troops to Afghanistan, which he does not forget to mention any of his critics.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive the gold medal, diploma and a cheque for ten million Swedish crowns (approximately 24 million Czech crowns).
He's planning to donate the paraffin to charity, but he hasn't decided yet which organization.
During the entire programme, the President and his wife will attend a banquet, as well as the Norwegian kings, the Prime Minister and 250 other guests.
Obama from the beginning had a rather reserved attitude towards the award.
He mentioned, for example, having the feeling of not being fully deserving.
He also repeated several times that the award is not only for him, but for all those who fight for the same values as him.
Immediately after the announcement he mentioned that it represents "a challenge to take action".
