USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is funny that Barack Obama, the president with the reputation of being the smartest man, like a diligent student repeats on the Afghan issue the strategy of his predecessor, whom he himself considered the dumbest.
When he finally revealed his long-awaited Afghan approach, it turned out to be a copy of the script Bush used for Iraq, created three years ago.
Not only is the phrase "as in Iraq" used several times in the same text, but he also did not hesitate to use the title of Bush's January 2007 statement for his own statement: "A new way forward".
It was he who three years ago criticized Bush's idea of sending new military reinforcements to Iraq, a country suffering from civil war, calling it "an irresponsible decision with catastrophic consequences".
The following months, however, proved that Bush's strategy, based on the recommendations of field captains, was the only possible and successful one, so that today there is no mention of Iraq in the news.
Bush's reputation did not improve, however objectively it left his successor with a much more favourable starting position than could have been expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama is hoping for a repeat of the miracle.
Field captains again asked him to increase the military contingent, most notably the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation General Stanley McCristal.
He asked for 40,000 men to improve the situation.
The president hesitated for three months, but he couldn't think of anything better, so at least he fooled the general about 10,000 troops.
He managed to get Europe to promise him another 5,000, although he himself had previously counted on at least 10,000.
The most problematic part of the whole Obama strategy seems to be his goal, to start withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete this procedure in three years.
Many doubt that the increase will bear the same fruit as the procedure in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well organized, its leaders respecting agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is different: no one can be trusted and no agreement is being honoured.
Under these conditions it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, if they are used to changing their commander every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, though formally established, will remain only a Potemkin people.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extraordinarily complicated due to the confused relations, further complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even establishing a state that is "capable of action", a minimum objective of the entire operation, seems very real.
The horizon of Obama's strategy is shattered by his volunteerism.
Over the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has continued to deteriorate and is now on the verge of exploding.
Only a romantic soul, who knows nothing of reality, can believe that the military sent to war to "come home soon", will do some miracle here.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is sheer irresponsibility, as the Taliban will view it as an indirect declaration of American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that Europeans are less and less willing to participate in military operations in Afghanistan.
European politicians do not know, nor do they want to explain to their constituents, what relation the security of Germany or Italy has to the war with the Hindu Kush.
The other factor, which can radically affect the situation, is the development of events in Iran.
If the situation continues to worsen and the increased sanctions have no effect on the Iranians, the US will have to make a difficult decision: try to solve the problem with military force or not.
The answers will have to be sought precisely when, according to Obama, America begins the triumphant withdrawal of troops from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will mean a dramatic setback for the Afghan situation.
The only positive for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years until the presidential election and therefore there is still plenty of time to find another strategy, if this one proves a total failure.
