The secret of the splendour over Norway solved: the Russians tested a missile
A special light effect of unknown origin was observed over Norway.
The Russian Defense Ministry finally acknowledged yesterday that near the borders with Norway it tested an intercontinental ballistic missile.
The launch failed again, and the Bulava missile, once intended to be the pride of the Russian military, is becoming the nightmare of Russian generals and Prime Minister Vladimir Putin.
Even their repeated presence in missile tests has not had the desired effect on the success of the test flights.
Bulava, in most cases, didn't fly out or there was a failure in the air.
The Russian newspapers write of "Bulava" as "a missile that does not fly".
A missile that doesn't fly, but it shines.
During this, the 13th test, there was no problem at first.
At the end of the flight, there were again technical problems with the aircraft.
The engine probably blew up in the third stage of the missile.
This time "Bulava" was launched from the nuclear submarine Dmitry Donskoy, which was floating submerged in the White Sea.
This type of missile allows it to be launched from a vessel that is moving and submerged at the same time.
So it's likely that the mysterious light over Norway, caused by an unidentified flying object, was actually the failed "Bulava".
The Norwegians did not hesitate from the beginning to believe that it was a Russian missile.
The generals this time defend themselves by claiming that you can't just talk about failure.
The first two stages of the missile held and the failure occurred in the third.
In the previous cases the engines broke down immediately at the first stage.
Although none of the launches were completely error-free, according to the Ministry of Defence management only six of the thirteen were unsuccessful.
The success of almost fifty percent fills the generals with optimism and so they continue to claim that "Bulavá" will one day fly without problems and that it will even manage to carry up to ten hypersonic nuclear blocks, whose total maximum weight is 1.15 tons.
