Czech discovery: a drug effective even on 'strayed' HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow the spread of HIV in the body
The main advantage of this improved substance is the fact that it is also effective against drug-resistant viruses.
In some cases this is more important than the fact that the compound is not as effective on a common variant of the virus, as some drugs already available.
AIDS is not curable yet.
However, the lives of patients can be significantly extended by a combination of drugs that prevent the HIV virus from replicating in the body.
However, its use has many side effects.
If the replication of the virus is not completely suppressed, so-called resistant viruses will be created; against them, drugs no longer work.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Czech Academy of Sciences, VŠCHT Prague and Heidelberg University shows that it is possible to overcome virus resistance.
They showed that substances called metallocarborans have an effect on albumin, which is responsible for the spread of HIV.
Metalocarborans are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus in a way that is different from all the drugs used today, and so they can solve the problem of resistance.
In their work, scientists find new, improved compounds, prepared by knowing the molecular mechanism of their binding to the albumin of the virus.
Metalocarborans have a unique three-dimensional structure: two polyhedral cages composed of boron, hydrogen, and carbon atoms are joined by the metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
HIV protease is an albumin of the HIV virus, and it is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease, HIV virus fractionation would not occur and mature, infectious virus corpuscles would not be created.
If we stop HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient's body, the scientists explain in a press release published by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the Czech Academy of Sciences.
In an article published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, scientists describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are joined by a short organic series, which is still being systematically modified.
A little weaker, but more effective.
Testing of the effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was performed in a test tube, and also against its resistant variants, obtained from HIV patients.
The effect of the metallocarborans on the common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as in clinically used drugs, however they do not lose their effect on resistant variants, in which the drugs often do not work.
The unique effect mechanism, its other qualities such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of other chemical modifications make metallocarbons interesting compounds for research with the aim of proposing effective HIV drugs, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Laboratory of Structural Biology at the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics at the Academy of Sciences.
