In On Thin Ice, Richard Ellis, a writer and illustrator, paints a natural history of the northern icon, the polar bear.
A connoisseur of the complicated history and politics of whaling, he describes the long tradition of Arctic explorers who proved their courage in the face of the polar bear.
Admiral Nelson's encounter as a brave 14-year-old cadet, fighting only with the tip of his musket, is surely a myth, but others are true.
The cubs, caught swimming along the bodies of their newly exterminated mothers, were trapped and sent to zoos and circuses.
