Ellis turns to accounts from other writers and historians, and often returns to the threat that hunters pose to the survival of the species.
Although banned in Norway, the United States, and Russia, the killing continues in Greenland and Canada, where helicopter hunters and snowmobile-riding Eskimo Indians use high-powered assault rifles to shoot down their prey.
Ironically, it is in the waters north of those two hunter nations that the ice will last the longest.
In his new book, After the Ice, Alun Anderson, a former editor of New Scientist, offers a clear and chilling account of Arctic science and a startling look at how the future of the Arctic can be transformed.
It's not like scientists have all the answers.
Neither atmospheric scientists nor oceanographers can adequately explain the speed of change.
It's not for lack of effort.
