UN group outlines plan to reduce emissions
The UN-sponsored climate conference, so far characterized by defiant stances and mutual recriminations, drew renewed attention on Friday with the release of a document that envisions ambitious reductions in greenhouse gases over the next 40 years, with industrialized nations bearing the brunt of the burden in the short term.
The text, which could provide the basis for a final political agreement to regulate greenhouse gases, highlighted the remaining obstacles and outlined the way forward.
But it was seen as a major breakthrough in a negotiation that is running out of time, with more than 100 world leaders arriving in Copenhagen next week.
Drafted by an ad hoc UN working group, the text does not say how much money rich countries would give to poor countries to tackle global warming in the short and long term.
And this offers a variety of options for key questions, including how developed economies and major emerging economies would cut their coal production, and what would be the limit of global temperature rise that policy makers would be willing to tolerate.
This gives the process a lot of flexibility, said John Coequyt, senior representative in Washington for the Sierra Club.
Michael Zammit Cutajar, who drafted the six-page document, summarized a 180-page negotiating text to focus on what the top UN climate official, Yvo de Boer, described as "the big picture".
It shows the profiles for a possible agreement, in which the industrialized nations would collectively cut their emissions by 2020 by between 25 and 45 percent, compared with 1990 levels, while the major developing countries would cut theirs over the same period by between 15 and 30 percent.
Together, countries would cut emissions by 50 to 95 percent by 2050.
The European Union also spurred talks on Friday, pledging to provide $3.6 billion annually over the next three years to help poorer countries adapt to the impact of climate change, from floods and droughts to deforestation.
Anyway, Friday featured the same kind of verbal fireworks that have dominated conversations over the past week.
The US special climate envoy Todd Stern rejected claims that call for mandatory greenhouse gas emissions cuts for industrialized countries, compared to volunteers from major emerging economies, if they were not funded by the developed world.
The move indicated that the Obama administration is taking a tougher line on China than Bush administration officials did just two years ago.
The United States will not make a deal without major developing countries moving forward and taking action, said Stern, who also regretted that the text did not do enough to ensure that cuts could be verified by external observers.
Stern made his comments an hour after Chinese Vice Foreign Minister He Yafei claimed that the top U.S. climate negotiator lacked "common sense", or was "very irresponsible" for saying earlier in the week that the United States would not help China economically to deal with global warming.
With the future economic trajectory of the world's major powers at stake, fault lines have erupted both within the developing world and between the industrial world and emerging economies.
The current battle is both to save individual economies and to save the planet, with China and the United States clashing over their respective obligations, while the poorest nations insist that the world's 24 most influential countries are ignoring the scientific imperative to take the boldest action.
Ricardo Ulate, a delegate from Costa Rica, said it is not surprising that major powers are arguing over who should pay for the costs of limiting greenhouse gases, even as vulnerable countries have become more aggressive in trying to hold big emitters accountable for their actions.
This is clearly a game where a new economic hegemony is being developed, said Ulate, who also works as a regional adviser on climate change in Mexico and Central America, for Conservation International.
Some of the countries most vulnerable to the impact of climate change indicated that they would continue to push for a legally binding treaty in Copenhagen, although most of the key participants say the talks will at most produce a political agreement.
The 43-member Alliance of Small Island States drafted a 24-page preliminary treaty proposal early Friday morning.
Artur Runge-Metzger, who heads international climate negotiations on behalf of the European Commission, said the push by small island nations has "put political pressure on the whole political process", in part because they are now unified and demanding action from emerging economies such as China and India.
Talks took on a new urgency as delegates focused on the fact that they must resolve most of the outstanding issues before the heads of government can reach a deal.
High-level officials, including Indian Environment Minister Jairam Ramesh and Chinese Deputy Minister, got off the planes and rushed to the Bella Center corridors, to closed-door meetings and press conferences, to delineate claims to be arbitrated over the next week.
The total disorder of the meeting (where 13,000 people enter and exit the convention center every day, activists playing guitar perform nightly shows mocking countries they say are selling out, and preliminary proposals are passed hand-to-hand instead of via email), poses a challenge.
The intensity only builds: almost all the key ministers are here right now, and on Wednesday 60 heads of government will be in Copenhagen.
We are entering the big leagues, said Carlos Manuel Rodríguez, vice president for global policy at Conservation International.
The heavyweights are coming.
Britain's first 140-mile-an-hour train redefines that feeling of Monday.
