The cradle of the dinosaur
The Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs - a six-foot-long [2.0 m] animal that ran on two strong hind legs, had an elongated head with sharp, curved teeth, short arms with sickle-shaped claws, and a long tail.
If the species had lived a couple of million years later, this one wouldn't have been anything special.
But Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs with these body features, Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues report in the journal Science on Thursday.
The species lived about 215 million years ago in what is now New Mexico, which was then in a dry zone of the supercontinent Pangaea at the equator.
Tawa opened a new window into the early evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It tells us a lot about the genealogical relationships, the spread and the characteristics of the first dinosaurs.
Nesbitt and other paleontologists began in 2006 an excavation at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we find a dozen dinosaur bones in a day - an unprecedented feat for Triassic sediments, reports Randall Irmis of the Utah Museum of Natural History.
Researchers quickly identified some bones as belonging to a new species.
In the course of the excavation they collected the remains of five specimens in total.
A new discovery confirms theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs
The name "Tawa" comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
Sterling Nesbitt says it is an exceptional find: "Triassic dinosaur fossils are extremely rare, usually only individual fragments".
Other dinosaur experts do not share that enthusiasm.
This finding is not particularly spectacular, but it confirms some theories about the ancient history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander of the University of Bonn.
According to current opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
But many of the oldest fossils are incomplete, so the classification of these early dinosaurs is quite controversial.
Thus, experts debate, for example, when the saurians were divided into their three most important genealogical lineages: the carnivorous theropods, which include Tyrannosaurus Rex, Velociraptor and also birds, the quadruped sauropods known as "long-neck" and their relatives, and the herbivorous Ornithischia (saurians with bird pelvis), to which belong, for example, the species Triceratops and Stegosaurus.
According to analysis by Nesbitt and his colleagues, Tawa hallae is a primitive theropod.
This shows an interesting combination of primitive and progressive properties, says Nesbitt.
For example, in the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found evidence of air sacs, such as those found in the descendants of theropods, birds.
Thanks to air sacs, birds breathe more efficiently than mammals.
In the case of Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were also evidently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive theropod with air sacs, says Randall Irmis.
Because the related lineage of later giant sauropods also possessed air sacs and light bones, it was likely that the common ancestors of both groups had already produced this useful innovation.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the earliest dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, researchers infer that the dinosaurs first appeared there.
Thus, the three genealogical lineages initially separated and spread from South America to all corners of the earth, which at that time still formed a single landmass, the supercontinent Pangaea.
However, the facts say that the team found along with Tawa hallae the remains of two other theropods not very closely related.
All three cannot descend from a single related ancestor, the researchers argue.
We believe there were at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the Science study.
Of course, there are also opponents.
An even older species, Silesaurus, a sister group of dinosaurs, lived in what is now Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His view may be distorted, for simply in South America many dinosaur fossils remain preserved, while on other continents there is little to discover.
The question of how dinosaurs managed to evolve from a relatively rare collateral lineage of reptiles to the dominant land vertebrates of the Mesozoic remains a mystery.
Meanwhile, in the Triassic dinosaurs still shared their living space with many other reptiles, for example with the ancestors of today's crocodiles and pterosaurs and with many other saurians.
Towards the end of the Triassic dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species developed, while the kin became extinct at the Triassic to Jurassic boundary.
Success stories didn't last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs survived by chance, but the other reptiles didn't.
Or dinosaurs were better adapted, so they could beat their rivals in the area.
Success stories aren't always eternal.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact halted the rise of a group of species, which had also already evolved in the Triassic and since then led a miserable existence: mammals.
