Dreamy worlds
In the waking state, some people see images and hear voices that others do not see or hear.
It is not only the mentally ill and drug addicts who blur the lines between imagination and reality.
As long as it happens in your sleep, everything's in order.
When we lie in our dark rooms with our eyes closed, we can indulge unhindered in the wildest imaginations and creations of fantasy.
However, anyone who experiences sleep-like states during wakefulness, or sees and hears things that others do not see or hear, is most often considered a madman or a drug addict, or at least a maniac, in the modern Western world.
But such images and voices do not only arise in the mentally ill or in drug addicts.
The fault lies with our imagination: the same neural processes that allow us to design houses, paint pictures, or write novels sometimes blur the lines between sleep, madness, and reality.
Dream-modified states of alertness can appear in a variety of forms, in the best of cases we call them visions, and in the worst, madness.
Although triggers and effects can be distinguished, similar processes can be referred to as visions of the mystic Hildegard von Bingen, psychedelic experiences of the New Age prophet Carlos Castañeda, states of shamanic possession, and psychosis and hallucinations.
Hallucinations or delusions occur when the balance of neuronal communication substances in the brain - especially dopamine, norepinephrine, serotonin and acetylcholine - is disturbed and the interaction between different parts of the brain is disturbed.
During schizophrenic psychosis, complex hallucinations and crazy thoughts are very common.
Gravity no longer has power over him.
The relationship between madness and sleep has occupied philosophers and doctors since ancient times.
Aristotle conceived of hallucinations as a form of sleep in the waking state, Wilhelm Griesinger, one of the founders of modern psychiatry, noted in 1861 a "great resemblance of the state of madness to the dream states", for Sigmund Freud, sleep was even "a psychosis, with all its nonsense, crazy formations, and mirages".
It's the fall of 2001, when Henning T. becomes a comic book character.
His body is two-dimensional and outrageously colorful.
Gravity no longer has power over him, he's floating near the ceiling of the room.
He feels a kick.
Behind him, figures of wings, blood-red faces, deformed, gnashing their teeth.
They're chasing him, kicking him with heavy, flaming boots, throwing him against the walls, he feels the pains all over his body.
Shrill, evil voices echo from the walls and the radio.
He can't take it anymore, the voices that insult and offend him.
Henning T. pulls two wires from the stereo, ties them together to form a hanging knot, and fixes them to a hook in the ceiling.
You climb on a horn and tie the knot around your neck.
Jump in there.
The rope is loose.
"Let it be a lesson to you!" shout the voices in a chorus that bursts his eardrums, "go to the clinic and get cured!"
Now, Henning T. is 40 years old and has experienced six acute psychosis episodes, the last two years ago, the first almost 20 years ago.
The cause that produced it was LSD.
His diagnosis is schizo-affective-paranoid psychosis, and he's also manic-depressive, taking medication, antidepressants, mania, schizophrenia.
He's learned to live with his illness, he's been married for three years.
In psychosis I have experienced the most terrible anguish and the deepest despair, he says.
Hallucinations are a cruel reality.
About one percent of the population falls ill with schizophrenia at least once in their lifetime; in psychiatric clinics it is treated as the second most common illness after depression.
In acute schizophrenic psychosis, most often the affected can no longer distinguish between the outside world and the inside world, and they fall into a state of overexcitement that can lead to hallucinations, delusions of grandeur, relationship disorders, or persecutory mania.
Especially widespread is hearing voices: voices that give orders, comment or dialogue.
Optical hallucinations are also common.
The sufferer is no longer able to distinguish between what is important and what is not, the brain can no longer filter out disturbing signals, the consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like sleep, psychosis also opens the floodgates to a torrent of ideas and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is subject-centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the general psychiatry clinic at Heidelberg University Hospital.
The schizophrenic is at the center of events, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he enters into a passive role, as in a dream, he feels overwhelmed by events and cannot organize them actively.
That's why schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
It's generally not possible to adjust reality to them, hallucinations are a cruel reality, waking up, impossible.
Having experienced a hallucination once in your life
Unlike in a dream, says Fuchs, "the spatial and sensory structure of reality that is perceived in psychosis remains in principle unchanged".
Paranoid thoughts and hallucinations are grounded in reality, the distancing of experience takes place in reality.
For researchers, it's still a mystery why our brains go wild.
According to Fuchs, states of emergency can cause anyone to lose contact with reality temporarily.
But not everyone develops a psychosis.
There seems to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that there are other determining factors besides genes.
Researchers assume that those affected suffer minimal brain damage.
We suspect that the neuronal maturity of the brain is affected at an early stage of development, such as through a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
But it is still a mystery how this alteration of the neuronal system occurs, which also does not manifest itself at all for many years.
Environmental influences also play a role  stress or a traumatic experience can be the triggers for a psychosis when a predisposition already exists.
Similarly, hallucinogenic drugs can cause psychosis by interfering with the brain's transmitter system.
When the brain gets hot
The illogical thing about all this is that psychotic people suffer from their hallucinations and take expensive drugs to get rid of them, while others pay for drugs that allow them to experience some, says Professor of Psychology Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Whether or not you perceive a hallucination as pleasant often depends on your point of view.
Kasten has been collecting reports on hallucinations and visions for ten years and has analyzed the results in the book Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf (The unreal world in our head), published last year.
Hallucinations are among the typical symptoms of psychosis, but also, surprisingly, of many other diseases.
These include, alongside mental disorders such as borderline personality disorder or depression, often also diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis, Alzheimer's and head and brain injuries.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brains of healthy people also hallucinate.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, are made up of memories that are normally repressed.
They arise when the areas of the brain where sensory perceptions are processed are overactive or under-contained; when our brains get hot, but also when we lack stimuli.
Drugs can cause this state in the same way as brain damage or psychosis.
But also restriction of stimuli, stress, love sickness or other exceptional brain states.
In younger studies, up to one third of the respondents have experienced a hallucination at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. was 16 years old, living in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attending a secondary school.
A common girl.
If it wasn't for those images and voices.
Sometimes during recess, a clumsy boy with long, dark hair addresses him.
When she answers, the other students look at her in surprise; no one but her hears or sees the boy.
They think the shy girl is a bit of a strange dreamer, but Sarah K. knows she's not dreaming.
She's awake and she sees and she hears that boy, just like she sees and she hears the girl sitting on the bench next to her.
You can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It's a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Sometimes she wonders if she's crazy.
He also knows that the boy and the rest of the visions are not real and disappear.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
Visions are often a burden.
When he's in class sometimes he can't follow the lesson because the teacher  to his eyes and ears  is introducing a new classmate, while to the rest he explains mathematical equations in a visible and audible way.
At night, the apparitions are alarming.
While waiting in the dark room for sleep, which often comes late and is scarce, she cannot tell whether she is awake or dreaming, whether the images she sees, the grimaces or the girl with bloody cuts on her arms and legs, appear before her eyes open or closed.
Leave me alone, he shouts at the figures.
She hasn't told her parents or friends anything, they'd think she's crazy.
Autumn of 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She passed selectivity last year and lives with her boyfriend.
The hallucinations have been gone for a year.
Since you've been in contact over the Internet with psychologist Kasten, you know you're not crazy.
Madness is also a work of art out of desperation.
According to Kasten, when a person is socially isolated or suffers from a restriction of stimuli, it is very likely that after a while he will begin to hallucinate.
I think the brain is busy and is looking for entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children when she was young and often played alone.
Her hallucinations began when, at age 13, she learned that the man she has called Dad since she has the use of reason is not her biological father.
Because visual and auditory hallucinations are active in the same areas of the brain that also process real impressions and sounds, sufferers like Sarah K. find it difficult to distinguish between visions and reality. "Every experience", Kasten says, "takes place in the brain, reality is projected there.
Hallucinations are also images produced by the brain, which is why they seem so real".
Kasten also classifies nighttime fantasies as a form of hallucination.
The hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from those of acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to recognize their visions as unreal.
Kasten therefore recommends that his patients regard their hallucinations as a special ability.
Borderline between sleep and hallucination
In this world too focused on the conscious, imaginary experiences are often pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, professor at Heidelberg and chief physician of the clinic of psychiatry and psychotherapy at the Florence-Nightingale-Krankenhauses hospital in Düsseldorf.
A psychosis is a hard and painful disease but one that also involves something positive and creative. Madness is a work of art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard has investigated what is called oneirism, a special form of consciousness, which is perceived as if it were a dream.
Dream hallucinations are almost complex and detailed dreams that the person experiencing them considers real and that later cannot be distinguished from being awake.
Dream states of consciousness arise in extreme situations associated with trauma or illness, such as in patients with polyradiculoneuropathy, who experience motor paralysis while fully conscious.
According to Schmidt-Degenhardt, when a person is threatened by a loss of self or the world due to a total and permanent motor disability, he replaces a very dangerous real situation with a world of his own and imaginary that is decoupled from reality.
A form of borderline between sleep and hallucination.
Since it is not possible to overcome a situation in reality, a world change occurs, although the real situation remains present in the imagination.
An intensive way of giving meaning and interpretation to an intolerable situation in itself that our own creative capacity allows us not to sink into the nothingness of loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in memory
Also the art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen, from Zurich, describes his dream experiences in his book Herzenwechsel as an action of soul saving.
He was 49 years old when his conscience set him on a multi-day journey following a heart valve operation with heart transplant included, while his body was doomed to immobility in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in a world he had created and visited strange places from other times: he found himself lying in bed, an elderly man on board a sanatorium on a train, a robot watching over his health.
He found himself in the High Middle Ages, surrounded by nobles who produced narcotics from blood.
A Greek on a motorcycle kidnapped him in his home country, surfed on his hospital bed in the firn Alps and ran into a Korean mobster.
It gives everything in these imaginary facts, everything is real, even later in the memories.
For Claussen, these inner journeys are fundamentally different from any dream.
Dreaming is a different state, so describe your experience.
On the contrary, memories of mental travel are, many years later, much clearer, even in irrelevant details.
Clearer and more intense even than real experiences.
The intensity of this experience dilutes the horizon of the rest of our everyday experiences, adds psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
Finally, oneirism, psychosis, hallucinations and drug use show how fragile the inner reproduction of external reality is, even when we are awake.
Each change in the state of consciousness, summarizes psychologist Kasten, "can lead to a distortion of what we call reality".
An experience that, on the other hand, can be completely enriching.
