The Promise of FonPeek
Peek is extremely limited, a device that only serves to look at mail, with no possibility even of seeing certain types of attachments or browsing the web.
It enjoyed its five minutes of fame in the US when Time magazine named it one of the products of the year.
Seeing it on the street is harder, I admit, but the idea can be interesting, especially for young people.
Unlike smartphones, Peek has a very low price and a very low monthly fee, less than half of what you pay, for example, for the iPhone data plan.
Seeing the success the company has released two new devices: one exclusively designed for Twitter, the other with a free lifetime data service in exchange for paying six times more for the Peek.
FonPeek, presented yesterday at the Le Web event, is the European version of the invention and its third incarnation.
It's as limited as its American counterpart, but it comes with a surprise.
The monthly maintenance fee of around EUR 12 per month includes roaming throughout Europe.
Those who travel with a smartphone already know what it's like to have to give up data when crossing the border or desperately search for a cafe with WiFi (or a Fon connection) to check the mail.
The idea of fixed-price roaming is incredibly attractive and should have been in place a long time ago.
Yes, some carriers have special deals and travel plans, but in my experience, you need a Ph.D. in physics to understand them and good glasses to read the fine print.
The European Commission's repeated efforts to achieve affordable roaming charges for all of Europe have barely had a noticeable effect.
Outside the home country, there is fear of using data, and rightly so.
That a device like FonPeek (which is curious to have the name Fon when it lacks Wifi) gets this kind of tariffs means that operators are starting to think differently and study different proposals to amortize their data network.
Kindle is another good example, it includes book download traffic and other Internet queries.
No contracts and no pipes.
It's a connected device, and you pay for it when you buy it, not month to month.
And that's what I hope to see someday with FonPeek, a lifetime access purchase option like the one Peek already has in the US.
Not because I'm going to buy it.
I'll check my mail on the phone, thank you.
I hope so because I think it's a fairer model for the consumer.
It would be interesting to see a computer with this same system.
