75% of working mothers have had problems at work because of their maternity
Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women in the younger generations who want to become mothers.
This is revealed by the study 'Fertility and the working life of women in Spain', produced by the CSIC in collaboration with the Women's Institute.
The survey of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75 leaves no doubt: 75% of working mothers have seen their employment opportunities limited because of motherhood.
The study points out that there are many differences in the start of cohabitation and the number of children, depending on whether they work or not and the type of work they do.
Women who do not have an activity outside the home, work part-time or have a precarious job, start living together earlier, have earlier first childbearing and more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, delay cohabitation and motherhood, and have fewer offspring.
"Women between 35 and 49 years old with a fixed job have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after starting a life together, a figure that increases to 4.1 women with fixed jobs have needed more time in their life to get them, which has led them to postpone union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of work performed has a great influence on maternity, although less on the calendar of mating", explains CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of education is another factor that differentiates the age of women when they marry and when they have their first child.
The higher the education level, the higher the age at which they marry and have their first child, the survey found.
The difference also persists among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those with primary and higher education have become mothers for the first time at 25.1 and 32.1 years of age respectively on average.
"Another division is also made between women according to their level of education.
While those with elementary education get married and have their first child before getting a stable job, those with middle or higher levels reverse this sequence and give priority to obtaining a stable job as a condition prior to marriage and the arrival of a child", Delgado details.
