Emergency braking assistance is now mandatory
As happened with ABS anti-lock braking and will happen with ESP stability control, emergency braking assistance systems will have to be a mandatory feature in European cars.
In fact, they are already in all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest a grace period is set until the end of February 2011.
The measure, imposed by the European Union, aims to increase pedestrian protection but, by its way of working, can also help to avoid many collisions within reach.
The emergency brake assistant increases the pressure on the brakes in case of an emergency, which the system detects by the driver's footstep.
But this one doesn't always keep that pressure up to the end.
According to a study by the Bosch car component manufacturer, one third of the drivers involved in an accident had not even hit the brake before the collision and half of them did not use all their force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum from the braking system, reducing the distance used by the car to stop.
According to a study by the EU itself, if all cars were equipped with these types of elements, up to 1,100 fatal pedestrian accidents could be avoided per year.
The reduction will be even greater - it is estimated that one in four accidents with injuries to people would be avoided - when the so-called intelligent emergency braking system is popularized.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that (via a radar or camera) detects obstacles and warns the driver, as well as acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, he helps by increasing the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If it does not react, and even if the collision is inevitable, the device applies maximum force to the brakes to minimize damage.
